answers.body_markdown:
I don&#39;t think your code is gonna work - there are multiple problems with it: 

first of all window&#39;s `load` event is probably not going to fire for your data request. 

secondly - attaching an event listener is a &quot;side effect&quot; you should wrap it inside a `useEffect`. (however we shouldn&#39;t be using that event here) https://reactjs.org/docs/hooks-effect.html

In `React` - try to avoid using `document.find***` or other helpers to get DOM nodes (again, usually you don&#39;t need to change dom nodes directly) If you need to have access to a DOM node, use `ref`. https://reactjs.org/docs/refs-and-the-dom.html

and in React in 99.99% cases you shouldn&#39;t modify DOM directly - let `React` handle that - you should provide react components with proper `state` and let your components render directly.

---

OK how do we solve your problem here? 

&gt; loading gif run on top of it all until all my data outputs on the DOM

So from this I think we should:

1. have a state flag (let&#39;s say `loaded`) that tracks if data has been fetched.
2. hide the loading animation when `loaded` is true. (and assuming we are still doing that with css)

How do we do that?

So in your loader component, it should take a prop `hidden` - when it is true, we add the `hidden` class to the loader - so it is going to look like this:

```jsx

const LoadingGif = ({ hidden }) =&gt; {
  return (
    &lt;div id=&quot;loader&quot; className={`loader ${hidden ? &#39;hidden&#39; : &#39;&#39;}`}&gt;
      &lt;img
       //...
      /&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  );
};
```

And in your `App` add a field to your state to track if your data has been loaded:

```
state = {
  // ... your other states
  loaded: false
};
```

when your fetch completes, make sure to update it to `true` 
```
    const data = await getData.json();
      this.setState({
        author: data.copyright,
        date: data.date,
        explanation: data.explanation,
        title: data.title,
        url: data.url,
        loaded: true  // here
      });
```

in your render, provide that `loaded` state to your loader component as a prop:


```
// it is hidden when `loaded` is true
&lt;LoadingGif hidden={this.state.loaded} /&gt;
```

Putting it together:

https://codesandbox.io/embed/patient-resonance-s3si9

